Usage: run --help
       run --conf <conf-file> --v4 [<kind>:]<config> --v6 [<kind>:]<config> [OPTION...]

Required arguments:
       --conf <conf-file>         Sets configuration policy table.
       --v4 [<kind>:]<config>     Device kind and configuration parameters
                                  for the Internet-side interface.
       --v6 [<kind>:]<config>     Device kind and configuration parameters
                                  for the B4-side interface.

Optional arguments:
       --ring-buffer-size <size>  Set the Intel 82599 receive buffer size.
       --cpu <cpu>                Bind the lwAFTR to the given CPU.
       --real-time                Enable real-time SCHED_FIFO scheduler.
       -D <seconds>               Duration in seconds.
       -v                         Verbose (repeat for more verbosity).

Deprecated arguments:
       --v4-pci <pci-addr>        PCI device number for the INET-side NIC.
       --v6-pci <pci-addr>        PCI device number for the B4-side NIC.
       --virtio                   Use virtio-net interfaces instead of Intel 82599.

Device kinds and configuration parameters:

       intel82259:<pci-addr>
             Intel 82259-based PCI NIC. The parameter is the PCI address of
             the NIC. (Alias: intel10g:<pci-addr>).

       virtio:<pci-addr>
             virtio-net PCI NIC. The parameter is the PCI address of the NIC.
             This can be used to bypass the kernel in an emulated environment.
             (Alias: vpci:<pci-addr>).

       tap:<interface>
             Use a TAP interface. The parameter is the name of an interface,
             which must be created beforehand using "ip tuntap".

       raw:<interface>
             Attach to an existing kernel-managed network interface using
             a raw packet(7) socket. The parameter is the name of a network
             interface (e.g. "eth0").
